From: chrisl@ncms.org (Chris Lang)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: 20 Aug 1993 14:31:23 -0400

This entire thread has got to be the dumbest one to grace these newsgroups
in a long time.  The initial "features" list was obviously compiled by
someone who was using at least year-old data, since the answers for
both Linux and NT were wildly out of sync with reality.  In particular
the claims about disk space and memory image size seem to imply that the
person in question had never actually installed either operating system
or tried to run it.

I run NT both at work and at home, and have off and on for 8 months.  I
have also been running Linux at home for about 8-9 months, so I think I
know whereof I speak.  It is upsetting to see supporters of both
sides undermining their own credibility by offering only lies and name-calling
instead of fact-based debate.  Since I consider myself both an NT
supporter and a Linux supporter, I feel particularly embarrassed by it. :-)

Only a fool can believe any more that there will be a single winner in the 
OS wars, whether it be NT, OS/2, or any flavor of Unix.  Why not turn 
some of this energy away from making up ridiculous and ignorant claims 
about competing operating systems, and turn it instead toward making 
the system of your choice the best it can be.  The proof is in the 
pudding, after all.

The whole situation boils down to:
1) NT is a good operating system -- very late, and rather more 
   resource-hungry than I would have liked, but very powerful.  
2) Linux is also very impressive, particularly considering its
   "humble origins", and becoming moreso all the time.  Use whichever 
   fits the need.

My own personal wish would be to see a Linux subsystem for NT.  Then I could
run NT running Linux running Windows running DOS running a telnet session 
back to...  no, I'd better stop now.

 -Chris

-- 
Chris Lang                      |   Technology Integration, Inc.
chrisl@ncms.org                 |   3025 Boardwalk
+1 313 995 4042                 |   Ann Arbor, MI  48108

