From: lukka@klaava.Helsinki.FI (Tuomas J Lukka)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: 20 Aug 1993 22:53:02 +0300

In article <930820201354.23255@world> brileary@world.std.com (Brian Leary) writes:
>A few neutral observations in this subject:

Your observations are really neutral, I see... let's dissect them.

>Observation #1:
>Making fun and degrading remarks about Windows users is fashionable in
>the linux groups. Linux users have the moronic idea that they must be
>somehow mentally and morally superior to the rest of the world. Snide
>remarks about how stupid and gullible Winodws users are are all but
>uncommon in the linux groups.

How very neutral to use adjectives like 'moronic'.
The snide remarks are actually less common than you think... comp.unix.misc
has a lot more of them. Some of them exist, true, but not all think that
way. It's just because we get our work more easily done through unix and
find that many popular interfaces (including windows gui) are really inferior
when doing real work. But this is a matter of opinion.

>Observation #2:
>The above is mainly due to the strong SHEEP MENTALITY running in the
>linux community. Few if any linux users have their own mind, After
>all, why bother? It's easier to just echo what a master sheep has
>said. This is obvious in their "rebuttals" to the check list that was
>posted here. Each one just echoes the other -- all of them asserted
>that linux has QIC-80 support, just because the first one said so,
>even though linux HAS NO QIC-80 SUPPORT, nor is likely to have it any
>time soon.

But QIC-02 we do. Someone made a mistake. Does NT support 4 IDE disks?
And how easily do you adjust a microsoft driver to do something like that?
With no source?

>But that's not all, there is also the LYNCH MOB MENTALITY. After
>hearing about how dum and gullible we are for two years, as soon as an
>objective comparison that shows that linux is not the ultimate os is
>posted here, the linux lynch mob mentality takes over, and we're
>burried by an article after another of vulgar flames. Even though the
>comparison was not posted to their group.

The comparison was posted to comp.os.linux.misc. If that's not our
group, then what is? Ever heard of cross-posting? I don't read
any ms groups.

>Of course, there is also the FANATIC MENTALITY, but that one is
>obvious.

Hmmmm, what were you saying about snide remarks???
And sheep, lynch mob and fanatic mentality? When someone tries to correct
some facts in a posting, you jump on us for posting vulgar flames?
An OBJECTIVE comparison? The only mistake in the corrections (about 80%
of the items were corrected) was QIC-80. 

>Observation #3:
>For a long time they kidded us about how NT is vaporware. The general
>consensus among them is that NT will never see the light of day, and
>our replies that it is coming out "soon" were laughed at. But look at
>what they are saying right now: Loadable device drivers... "soon",
>Drag and drop... "R6 is out any day now", Running ODS apps...
>"emulator is coming along nicely", Running Winodws apps... "WABI is
>almost here", ..etc. ..etc. What a joke!

The OS has been here. The development is open, and free. You can
give a hand. With NT, you eat what the MS engineers gave you.
Also, it has been mentioned elsewhere that your first items:
loadable device drivers, drag&drop and dosemu are already there.
WINE (wabi) is coming along, but there I can SEE the development,
estimate when it will be ready. None of the MS delays. I can even
get the code and help if I wanted.

>Observation #4:
>Linux is inferior to DOS! How's that? Well, DOS has loadable device
>drivers, linux doesn't. Your printer and modem use the same IRQ? No
>problem in Windows, just don't use them at the same time. In linux,
>you have to use the modem a little, stop, recompile the kernel with
>the printer enabled and the modem disabled, use the printer a little,
>stop, recompile, use the modem, stop, ...etc. Two drivers that use the
>same IRQ cannot live in the same kernel, even if none of them is used!

Loadable device drivers, as I said, are there.
But does DOS do two DOS apps next to each other? 
What about virtual consoles? Long filenames? 
This is just like the comments about NT not having a command-line interface.
Misinformation and fanaticity.

>Observation #5:
>Not only that linux doesn't support drag an drop, its users have no
>concept of what drag and drop is! Most of them think it's just cut and
>paste, as can be seen clearly in the "rebuttals".  The only way to get
>drag and drop in linux is to pay $299 (NT is less expensive, how
>ironic) to buy Motif, and virtually no Motif application makes use of
>it anyway, and you cannot drag and drop between Motif and Xaw
>applications.

What's your point? Should I really buy NT so I can drag and drop some
funny items between some applications? Are you really serious?

>Observation #6:
>Linux users have no idea what multimedia support is.  Multimedia
>support is NOT that the os is able to talk to a sound card!  DOS can
>do that. It is that the os has inherent layering facilities to do
>multimedia. To run a full motion picture clip or play a MIDI song via
>the sequencer in Windows, you just call a single API function (e.g.
>MciSendCommand).

This is true. But most people are not so interested in having a midi
song played by a sequencer in windows, than in getting work done.

>Observation #7:
>QIC-80 support is not in linux, nor is it ever likey to be. The
>general consensus among linux developers is that QIC-80 is simply
>unsuitable to multitasking environments, a claim that's obviously
>disproved by NT's support for QIC-80.

So now you take this again... this was observation #1 already.

>Observation #8:
>Q: What does linux do when it runs low on memmory? A: IT FALTERS! The
>only os I have seen that locks up when it runs low in memory. Every
>linux user must constantly watch for memory useage, if linux needs a
>few more kilobytes than are available, it doesn't complain, it just
>crawls to a halt before dying a miserable death, taking down the whole
>system with it.

Not necessarily any more, as bad as it used to be.
Tell me: what does NT do?

>Need I say more? There is still lots to talk about: the flaky file
>system, the feeble networking, ..etc. ..etc.

What flaky file system? Xiafs has given me zero serious trouble.
No lost files, nothing. Only one time was there a hint of something, but
that was patchlevels and eons ago: some blocks were lost but a file system
check found them again promptly and I've heard nothing since.
Two machines, heavy use more than half a year. 

>Linux users, get a clue! Your os is shit. And remember, we didn't
>start this.

What a very objective and neutral statement!!! I commend you on maintaining
that friendly and neutral attitude throughout your article.
Have you ever run linux? If not, what do you know about it?

I don't know who started it, whether it was a ms'er or linuxer or someone
making an intentional flamebait... but this has been coming for a long time.

Next time, please don't say that you're neutral when you aren't. Please?
I admit right now to being non-neutral.

        Tjl


